### Exercise 2.2.3
The two code blocks below look similar but can produce different results. Without running the code, predict the output of each block when `score = 95`. Then run them and explain why the results differ.

```python
# Block A
if score >= 90:
    print("A")
elif score >= 80:
    print("B")
elif score >= 70:
    print("C")
else:
    print("F")
```

```python
# Block B
if score >= 90:
    print("A")
if score >= 80:
    print("B")
if score >= 70:
    print("C")
else:
    print("F")
```


<details>
<summary>Solution</summary>

::: {#0812f103 .cell execution_count=7}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Block A
score = 95

if score >= 90:
    print("A")
elif score >= 80:
    print("B")
elif score >= 70:
    print("C")
else:
    print("F")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
A
```
:::
:::


::: {#03f39176 .cell execution_count=8}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Block B
score = 95

if score >= 90:
    print("A")
if score >= 80:
    print("B")
if score >= 70:
    print("C")
else:
    print("F")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
A
B
C
```
:::
:::


Block A correctly prints `"A"`. But block B also prints `"B"` and `"C"` ‚Äî the wrong answer. In Block B, all three `if` statements are evaluated independently. For `score = 95`, all three conditions are `True`, so the print statement is executed three times: first `"A"`, then `"B"`, then `"C"`. The final `else` belongs only to the last `if`, so it does not affect the other branches. In Block A, `elif` stops evaluation as soon as the first `True` condition is found. Use `elif` whenever your branches are mutually exclusive.
</details>

