### Exercise 2.2.4
Write a conditional that checks a student's grade and assigns both a letter grade and a short feedback message to two separate variables called `letter` and `feedback`. Print the result as a single f-string. Use the thresholds below and test with at least two different grades.

- 90 or above: `"A"` ‚Äî `"Excellent work."`
- 80‚Äì89: `"B"` ‚Äî `"Good work."`
- 70‚Äì79: `"C"` ‚Äî `"Satisfactory."`
- Below 70: `"F"` ‚Äî `"Did not pass."`

<details>
<summary>Solution</summary>

::: {#e2f7aa54 .cell execution_count=9}
``` {.python .cell-code}
grade_score = 92

if grade_score >= 90:
    letter   = "A"
    feedback = "Excellent work."
elif grade_score >= 80:
    letter   = "B"
    feedback = "Good work."
elif grade_score >= 70:
    letter   = "C"
    feedback = "Satisfactory."
else:
    letter   = "F"
    feedback = "Did not pass."

print(f"Score: {grade_score} ‚Äî Grade: {letter}. {feedback}")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Score: 92 ‚Äî Grade: A. Excellent work.
```
:::
:::


::: {#7b2d2e1c .cell execution_count=10}
``` {.python .cell-code}
grade_score = 65

if grade_score >= 90:
    letter   = "A"
    feedback = "Excellent work."
elif grade_score >= 80:
    letter   = "B"
    feedback = "Good work."
elif grade_score >= 70:
    letter   = "C"
    feedback = "Satisfactory."
else:
    letter   = "F"
    feedback = "Did not pass."

print(f"Score: {grade_score} ‚Äî Grade: {letter}. {feedback}")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Score: 65 ‚Äî Grade: F. Did not pass.
```
:::
:::


Assigning multiple variables inside the same conditional branch is a clean and common pattern. Notice that both `letter` and `feedback` are always assigned regardless of which branch is taken, so they are safely available outside the conditional.
</details>

